#{\footnote UG_UTIL_PIC}
${\footnote Picture Utility}
K{\footnote PIC}
+{\footnote BW_UG_7}
{\b\f0{\cf2\scaps User's Guide: Utilities}\line\fs32 Picture Utility}\par\pard\sb100

This program is used to recolor and/or convert a number of image
 formats supported by the {\i XFile} library.  The recoloring
 operation is needed to force the bitmaps to use the {\i Van Gogh}
 palette, which is typically fixed for the lifetime of a given
 viewport.  In order to avoid costly real-time color conversion,
 this utility performs the processing off-line.
\par

The utility performs the following steps:
\par

Loads image and {\i Van Gogh} palette.
\par

Display any requested image information and/or palette entries.
\par

Converts an image to use the {\i Van Gogh} palette, if requested,
 either by recoloring an 8-bit image or converting the format.
\par

Saves image, if requested.
\par

The utility currently supports BMP, CEL, LBM, PCX, TGA, and XEB
 bitmaps as implemented by the {\i XFile} library.  Some formats
 don't support all bitdepths, so watch for errors.  See {\i XFile}
 for more details.
\par

{\cf2
Note:  When recoloring images, it is best to use a true-color
 input file since this will result in each pixel having the
 closest color match in the new palette.  Transparent bitmaps, however,
 require that an 8-bit image is used as the input with anything that is
 to be transparent set to color 255.
}\par

\line{\b\fs28 Usage}\par

pic [-q |  -i  | -s | -x | -m | -t <fname.pal>]\line
\tab [-p | -2 | -3 ] <fname.xxx> [-o <fname.xxx>]
\par

\line{\b\fs28 Options}\par

{\b -q}\par

By default, the utility outputs a number of status messages.
 This option directs the utility to operate silently.
\par

{\b -i}\par

This option directs the utility to display the original images
 statistics, including resolution and color-depth.
\par

{\b -s}\par

This option directs the utility to display the palette entries
 for the original image, if any.
\par

{\b -x}\par

This option will direct the utility to preserve any entries in an 8-bit
 image with index 255.  Since index 255 is used as a transparent color
 index in {\i Van Gogh}, this is needed to prevent the palette conversion
 from destroying these entries.
\par

{\b -m}\par

This option will direct the utility to convert the image to a {\i Van
 Gogh} monochrome Z-map image.  Index 255 is assumed to be a transparent
 color and is mapped to a 0 bit in the Z-map, otherwise it is a 1 bit.
 The result is saved to a .ZMP file (or the output file specified by -o).
\par

{\b -t <fname.pal>}\par

This option is used to specify the {\i Van Gogh} palette file to use
 for all operations.  By default, the file DEFAULT.PAL in the
 same directory as the PIC.EXE is used.
\par

{\cf4\scaps CHANGED}\line
{\b -p}\par

This option will direct the utility to convert the loaded image
 to use loaded palette.  This is the recolor/24-bit/32-bit to 8-bit
 operation.  For a 32-bit image, anything with an alpha less than 255
 is considered transparent.
\par

{\cf4\scaps NEW}\line
{\b -2}\par

This option will direct the utility to convert the loaded image
 to a 15-bit 2 bytes/pixel format.  This does not work on 8-bit images.
\par

{\cf4\scaps NEW}\line
{\b -3}\par

This option will direct the utility to convert the loaded image
 to a 24-bit 3 bytes/pixel format.  This does not work on 8-bit images.
\par

{\b -o <fname.xxx>}\par

This option is used to specify an output image file for the
 loaded and possibly converted image.
\par

\line{\b\fs28 Example}\par

To convert the file TEST.BMP into TEST.CEL using the {\i Van Gogh}
 palette TEST.PAL, the following command is used:
\par

{\f2
pic test.bmp -p -t test.pal -o test.cel
\par
}

